icator of economic vulnerability. Individual Pacific economies were assessed based on key indicators of macroeconomic soundness and the dependence on: income from offshore investments; commodity exports; tourism; and remittances; and supplemented by an update of economic conditions in the Pacific economies. This preliminary assessment concluded that: \u2022 Kiribati, Solomon Islands, and Tuvalu were most vulnerable; \u2022 Fiji Islands, Republic of Marshall Islands, Palau, and Tonga were highly vulnerable; \u2022 Cook Islands, Federated States of Micronesia, Samoa, and Vanuatu were vulnerable; and \u2022 Papua New Guinea, Nauru, and Timor-Leste were cushioned.30 1.20. In a subsequent report, the ADB noted that only Timor-Leste, Papua New Guinea and possibly Vanuatu were expected to continue to grow at adequate rates over 2009.31 Governments in PNG and Timor-Leste are now spending revenue saved during the boom period of high commodity prices.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "1925d1ea-5628-4944-9d55-1ef67e2b3c7d": {"__data__": {"id_": "1925d1ea-5628-4944-9d55-1ef67e2b3c7d", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/protecting-pacific-island-children-women-during-economic-and-food-crises", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Protecting Pacific Island Children & Women during Economic and Food Crises", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/protecting-pacific-island-children-women-during-economic-and-food-crises", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "1a857c0dbd05222a5bed5093b8afbddc62fac13edb88fd3d806b14f26e931415"}, "2": {"node_id": "63bf06c4-7068-42da-9583-44aa26e1df3d", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/protecting-pacific-island-children-women-during-economic-and-food-crises", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "8c19006071ea5b62cbb21f7b5fda44ad9366440831b601cf781b86a773b42bdb"}}, "hash": "51b9a4cb54498261877ca0b18e445e310e02bfb55013f522d8bb5c41a1e16e8a", "text": "This is helping support their economies during 2009 and into 2010. In these two economies, the income growth needed to help lift living standards and reduce poverty will continue for now, albeit at a slower rate in PNG. Real estate development and tourism remain firm in Vanuatu, partly because tourists appear to be diverting from the Fiji Islands, and this is expected to result in moderate growth in Vanuatu. Vanuatu is the largest recipient of Financial Direct Investment (FDI), however, and is likely to be affected as FDI decreases. An economic contraction (i.e., negative growth) is projected in Fiji Islands, Federated States of Micronesia, Palau, Samoa, and Tonga, and economic growth is expected to be low in most other Pacific economies. The contraction in gross domestic product (GDP) forecast for 2009 in the Fiji Islands and Samoa is likely to be larger than originally expected. Conditions are deteriorating rapidly in Solomon Islands due to a slump in the export of logs\u2014a huge concern given log exports account", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "caaf8fd0-0c08-4062-84ad-997ffac4a9c9": {"__data__": {"id_": "caaf8fd0-0c08-4062-84ad-997ffac4a9c9", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/pr